<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notesheet Entry</div>
<dl id="s17024ak"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17024ak">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../ff/unbs/s17all.htm#s17024ak">sector 24(ak)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> solid resist change of shape or division / liquid little &ditto / gas no &#x3003; &amp; tend to expand</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Bodies that <mark>offer resistance to change of shape or to division into parts are called <i>solids</i></mark>. <p>Bodies that offer <mark>practically no resistance to change of shape or to division into parts are called <i>liquids</i></mark>.</p> <p>Bodies that <mark>offer no resistance to change of shape or to division into parts, and <i>show a constant tendency to expand</i> or occupy more space are called <i>gases</i></mark>.</p> <small> Wentworth and Hill, <a name="TBOP" href="/udra/udex.htm#tbop"><cite title="source">A Text-Book of Physics</cite></a> (1904), 3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
